{
  "answer": "In *The Wanderer*, *wyrd* appears as an inexorable, impersonal cosmic force governing all earthly mutability: \"Wyrd is wholly steadfast!\"[^1] A weary mind \"cannot withstand Wyrd,\"[^2] but the poem's metaphysics—blending pagan fatalism with Christian hope—allows the wise exile to patiently endure it while seeking \"grace... from the Father in heaven.\"[^3]\n\nIn *Manusmṛti*, *daiva* names a lawful form of marriage (the second of eight), where a father ritually gives his adorned daughter to a priest amid an ongoing sacrifice: \"The gift of a daughter, after having adorned her, to a priest who is duly officiating at a sacrifice while it is in progress, they call the `Daiva` rite.\"[^4] Its metaphysics frames marriage as *dharma*-ordered action shaping progeny and ancestral merit—a son from a *daiva* wife \"frees seven generations before and seven after\" from sin.[^5] No broader discussion of *daiva* as cosmic fate appears in the corpus.\n\nWyrd permits patient endurance and supplication to the divine amid inevitable decay (an interior, contemplative action); *daiva* does not, demanding instead precise ritual performance within *varṇa* strictures to generate salvific outcomes.\n\n[^1]: *Old English Elegies*, \"The Wanderer\" [paragraph](/works/unknown-old-english-elegies-d5fe9e/11-the-wanderer/translation/#p-9cca5e).\n[^2]: *Old English Elegies*, \"The Wanderer\" [paragraph](/works/unknown-old-english-elegies-d5fe9e/11-the-wanderer/translation/#p-9462cc).\n[^3]: *Old English Elegies*, \"The Wanderer\" [paragraph](/works/unknown-old-english-elegies-d5fe9e/11-the-wanderer/translation/#p-5bdc65).\n[^4]: *Manusmṛti*, Chapter 3 [paragraph](/works/unknown-manusmrti-347b76/03/translation/#p-7c3179).\n[^5]: *Manusmṛti*, Chapter 3 [paragraph](/works/unknown-manusmrti-347b76/03/translation/#p-eb7526).",
